Aritotle defines an Efficient caue, to be that from whence the firt beginning of Mutation or Ret proceeds;
Metaph. l. 3. c. 2. & Phy. l. 2. c. 28. as an Advier; a Father; and imply, he that doth a thing, of the thing that is done; that which is the tranmutor, of that which is tranmuted. Whereupon many and undry kinds of caues, from whence a motion or mutation doth proceed, are brought and amaed in the Generation of Animals: ometimes an accident, or quality is aigned
the Efficient, and o the animal heat, and forming faculty are alledged, as the Efficient. Sometimes an external ubtance before exitent, in which the platical power, and forming faculty reides; as the father, or the eed of that creature by whoe efficacy the Chicken is procreated of the egge. Sometimes ome internal ubtance exitent by it elf; as the pirit, or Calidum innatum. And ometimes ome other ubtance; as the Form, or Nature, or Soul, or ome Vegetative part of the Soul: which kinde of principle, we have aid, is in the Egge.

Nor do prolifical eggs differ from improlifical, and ubventaneons in this, that the former contain the


Cocks eed (as Aldrovandus would have it;) nor is there found any thing done or coagulated in the egge by the eed of the male, or any enible alteration made, (for there is no enible difference at all between a prolifical, and an addle egge) and yet a prolifical, which is conceived a long time after coition, contains in it the power of both Sexes, and the capacity of being made, and of making a chicken: as if it had deduced its original from the coition of both Sexes, and their conent and conpiring together in one, as Aritotle would have it; 
                  De gen. an. l. 1 c. 18. who being preed by that argument, (as we have declared before concerning the generation of the egge) did contitute a oul in the egge; which if it be there, mut without cruple be the principle and efficient, of all thoe things which are naturally met with in the egge. For it is mot certaine, What thing oever at lat it prove which doth procreate the chicken out of the egge, (in whoe fabrick o much skill, o divine contrivance and providence is required; fitting eyes for ight, the bill for reception of the meat, the feet for walking, the wings for flight, and all the other Utenils for ome emploiment or other) that it is either a oul, or ele omething more worthy and excellent then a oul, working by widom and providence.

But it is manifet that the Seed of the Male is not the Efficient of the Chicken, neither an Intrument, by whoe motion the Chicken might be formed, (as Aritotle would have it) nor as an Animate ubtance, as if the oul were its oul. For in the egge there is no eed at all, either now touching it, or that ever did touch it, (and it is impoible that that hould move, which doth not touch; 
               Ibid. 
               or that any thing hould be affected by that, which doth not move it) and therefore the eeds oul ought not to be aid to be in it. And yet though the oul be the Efficient in the Egge, yet it doth not appear to be derived rather from the Cock, or his eed, then from the Hen.

And therefore Blood is found in every particle of the Body, nor can you find footing for the point of a needle, or the edge of your naile, where you hall not immediately tart the blood: as if, were it not for the blood, the body would enjoy no heat, nor life. Therefore the blood being never o little concentrated and fixt, (Hippocrates calls it, 
                  < in non-Latin alphabet >
               ) as it is in Swouning, frights, extream cold weather, and the approach of the Paroxyme or fit of an Ague, you hall preently behold, the whole body freeze, and grow tiff, and languih in a pale and livid complexion: but the blood being ummoned back, by applied Fomentations, exercie, or affections of the Mind, (as Joy, or Anger) how nimbly do all parts recover their Heat, Floridnee, Vigour and Beauty.

And latly, we do not ee that any thing is naturally produced out of fire, as a micible ubtance;


and perhaps it is altogether impoible there hould; ince fire (like a kind of living body) is in contiual flux, and eeketh utenance whereby it may be nourihed, and conerved: according to that of Aritotle, that fire onely is nourihed, and that chiefly becaue of its form. But whatoever 
                  De gen. & corr. l. 2. c. 50. is nourihed, cannot poibly be it elf mixed with its nutriment. Whereupon it followeth, that it is impoible for Fire to be micible. For Mition, according to Aritotle, is micibilium alteratorum unio, the union of micible things altered; where one micible thing is not transformed into another, but both of them being both active and paive in regard of themelves, do contitute a third thing: but generation (epecially that which is by a Metamorphois) is the ditribution of one imilar thing which is to be altered into divere more. Nor are mixt imilar bodies aid to be generated out of the Elements, but in ome ort to be contituted out of them: into which alo they are capable to be diolved.

And yet the Uterus hath its hare in this buines of Delivery: as hall appear in the following example. A poor woman, who was a Laundres, did for a long time labour under the Bearing down, or precipitation of her wombe, and the heath thereof did hang down to the bignes of ones fit, and at length, uing no applications to it, her grief grew o forcible upon her, that it now begun to reemble a Scrotum, the skin being rugged and qualid; and yet found now les paine or trouble in it, then he was formerly ued to find, when it newly bore down. But, he asking my advice, I counelled her to keep her Bed for ome certain dayes, and to mollifie the dryer parts thereof with fomentations, and oyntments, and o when her wombe was reduced into her body, to keep it till up with pearies and wathes, till by the ue of drying and trengthening remedies it was confirmed and etled in its proper place. The cure did for ome time ucceed to our wih; but he being poor, was fain to fall to her calling again, to get money, and o intermitting her appointed applications, he fell into a relape, and endured it pretty well, her womb ometimes retiring back again, and ometimes continuing quite out; but for the mot part, at night he did reduce it, and there it remained for ome time. But after many dayes, he addreed her elf to me again, complaining that her


               wombe being welled by the ue of her remedies, and epecially of her fomentations (as he conceived) would now no longer abide in her body. And yet applying ome oyntments which I had precribed, he had forced it in againe, but her cure did not continue long: for no ooner did he rie, and tand upon her leggs, and o goe about her work, but her wombe did preently, by reaon of its bulke and weight, diturbe her againe, and would eaily beare downe upon any occaion. And now at this time it was as large as a Bulls Cod, dangling between her leggs,: o that I upected, that not onely the heath, but that the womb it elfe was now inverted, or ele that hee was dieaed with a Uterine Hernia, or rupture. It grew at lat bigger then a mans head, being then a hard tumour, and hanging downe to her knees did much pain her, o that he could not goe (but upon all foure) and breaking jut in the bottom of it, it did effund a moiture (as if it had been an Ulcer) and blood with it. Looking upon it (for I did not explore it by touch) I did upect it to be a Cancer of the wombe, and therefore did bethink my elfe of a Ligature, and cutting it off: and in the interim, I advied her to apply gentle fomentations to it to awage the paine. But the following night, an Infant perfectly haped, of a pan long, was cat out of that Tumour, but it was dead; and the next morning they brought it to me; which having embowelled, I kept wimming in cold water without corrupting for ome moneths time, hewing it to many of my friends (as a miraculous pectacle.) The skin in this Foetus was not yet formed; but only a thin paring appeared (uch as lieth about a Codlin) which I eaily drew away whole and entire;


whereupon all the mucles dicloed themelves very ditinctly, (for the Foetus was leane.) What other matters I oberved in the diection of this Foetus, hall be related elewhere: in this place, I thought it onely convenient to ignifie, how the Matrix it elf alone did promote this Abortive, and did eject this Foetus by its owne indutry.
